---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Layout title="Universality" description="The HeadGenome taxonomy is architecture-intrinsic — not a property of data, language, or training distribution.">
<div class="page-top">
  <p class="eyebrow">02 — Universality</p>
  <h1>The taxonomy survives<br/>everything we threw at it.</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    Untrained controls. Permutation nulls. Cross-domain training.
    The four-class structure is not a property of language —
    it is a geometric necessity of the transformer architecture under gradient descent.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="section">

  <blockquote class="claim reveal">
    "All four models were trained on human language. Couldn't the structure be a property of English?"
    <footer>No. Here is the three-part proof.</footer>
  </blockquote>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">01 — The Initialization Null</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    A randomly-initialised GPT-2 has no meaningful V/Q structure — flat, noisy, no monotonic
    trend. After training, the same architecture develops the law to p ≈ 10⁻¹²⁷.
    Structure emerges from gradient descent on prediction objectives, not from the initialisation.
  </p>
  <figure class="figure reveal">
    <img src={`${base}/figures/fig8_universality.png`} alt="Initialization null" loading="lazy" />
    <figcaption>V/Q ratio in random-init GPT-2 (top) vs. trained GPT-2 (bottom). The monotonic law is absent before training and appears universally after it.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">02 — The Permutation Null</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    We feed the trained model randomly shuffled token sequences — same vocabulary, same lengths,
    but destroying all linguistic structure. The entropy-collapse probe still recovers the same
    four head classes. The V/Q scaling law still holds.
    Specialisation survives destruction of language statistics within a trained model.
  </p>
  <div class="callout reveal">
    Induction heads (Induction) show <em>equal or greater</em> entropy-collapse scores on shuffled
    sequences — they are not language detectors, they are structural pattern-copy detectors.
    Scatter in Local heads is a predicted outcome of their plastic precursor role.
  </div>
  <figure class="figure reveal">
    <img src={`${base}/figures/fig9_permutation.png`} alt="Permutation null" loading="lazy" />
    <figcaption>Entropy-collapse probe scores on natural vs. randomly-shuffled sequences.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">03 — The Cross-Domain Proof</h2>
  <p class="reveal">
    GPT-2 was trained on WebText. Qwen on a multilingual mix. Llama on a curated instruction
    corpus. Despite radically different training distributions, all four models obey the same
    V/Q scaling law with the same slope. The governing law is stable across radically different
    training distributions.
  </p>
  <figure class="figure reveal">
    <img src={`${base}/figures/fig10_crossdomain.png`} alt="Cross-domain proof" loading="lazy" />
    <figcaption>V/Q scaling law overlaid across all four architectures. Slope is consistent despite different model sizes, attention mechanisms, and training data.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="callout reveal">
    Together: the taxonomy is architecture-intrinsic — not a data artefact, not a language artefact,
    not a cherry-picked result. It is a structural property of how transformers specialise
    under gradient descent on prediction objectives.
  </div>

</div>
</Layout>
<style>
.section { max-width:820px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 2.5rem 8rem; }
.section h2 { font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3vw,2.2rem); font-weight:200; letter-spacing:-.04em; line-height:1.15; margin-bottom:1.25rem; }
.section p { color:var(--text-2); font-weight:300; line-height:1.75; margin-bottom:1rem; }
blockquote.claim {
  border: none; margin: 3rem 0;
  padding: 2.5rem 3rem;
  background: var(--bg2); border-radius: var(--radius);
  font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 200; font-style: italic;
  color: var(--text-2); line-height: 1.65;
}
blockquote.claim footer {
  margin-top: 1.25rem; font-style: normal;
  font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 200;
  color: var(--accent); letter-spacing: -.02em;
}
</style>
